sense.name: a typical example or standard for something
sense.examples: The main character of the story is the prototype of a middle-class American office worker. The prototype of all careerists is Judas. (example, illustration) Bob's friends see him as the prototype of a young Silicon Valley entrepreneur.

sense.name: a preliminary test model of an artifact
sense.commentary: PROTOTYPE[+entity][+artifact][+construction][+preliminary][+test] Note: implies a manmade purposive artifact
sense.examples: A prototype of the new building complex stood on a table at the architectural firm. They are building a prototype of a small rocket that will launch satellites into space. The product went from design board to prototype to beta test to shipment in under 24 months.

sense.name: an archetype or origin on which something later is patterned
sense.commentary: PROTOTYPE[+entity][+form][+model][+prior] [+relation][+origin][+archetype] Note: does -not- imply a purposive connection, but rather a natural, chronological one.
sense.examples: This is a skeleton of a creature that is the prototype for the modern horse. These objects are a prototype of a class of rapidly-spinning neutron stars.
